instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin’s Control Application operates as a Python process that consumes trajectories generated by the Trajectory Generator Service. A trajectory is a sequence of positional waypoints computed by a kinematic model that is intended to drive the crane without residual swing. The Control Application forwards these waypoints to the Physical Crane Interface, which translates them into low‑level motor/actuator commands sent to the crane controllers. The interface exposes no details on message format or authentication in the documents; it simply relays the high‑level commands to the physical hardware. Feedback from the physical system is captured by the Physical Crane Interface and recorded by the Logging Application for post‑hoc validation by the Continuous Validation Service."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is orchestrated following a microservice architecture depicted by the C4 Context and Container diagrams. The Physical Crane component streams real‑time sensor telemetry (acoustic, torque, motor currents, end‑effector position) to a central MQTT broker. The Control Application consumes these topics, invokes a Trajectory Generator service (implemented in Python/ROS) to compute optimal motion plans, and publishes plan packets to a dedicated MQTT topic consumed by the Crane control unit. A Simulation Service runs inside a Docker container; it subscribes to planned trajectories, forwards them to a physics‑based simulator (Gazebo, PyBullet), and returns simulated telemetry. All services – control, trajectory generation, simulation – are containerized, deployed on VMs (Ubuntu 20.04), and communicate via secure TLS‑enabled MQTT with QoS 1. Coordination is achieved by the broker; the Control Application acts as a central orchestrator, scheduling tasks and aggregating telemetry for ingestion into InfluxDB and visualization dashboards. The architecture follows a layered client‑server pattern with the Control Application as the orchestrator and the Crane actuator as the subordinate client."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "GreenhouseDT follows a lifecycle that starts with a C4‑model based architectural design where the greenhouse layout and sensor network are diagrammed. The implementation phase bundles the system into Docker containers that include an InfluxDB time‑series database, an ActiveMQ message broker, and a virtual‑machine image that provides pre‑recorded data for the greenhouse. Deployment is achieved via the pre‑configured VM image, enabling rapid installation on a host machine. During operation the twin collects real‑time sensor data through MQTT, writes to InfluxDB, and synchronises adaptations with the physical greenhouse. Evolution of the twin is governed by an ad‑hoc version‑control strategy recorded in the GitHub repository; changes are tracked by Git commits and the repository’s README document outlines the iterative development process."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "Inter‑service communication is performed via an MQTT broker that acts as the messaging backbone for the Trajectory Generator Service, Simulation Service, and Continuous Validation Service, using MQTT's publish/subscribe semantics over TCP/IP (default port 1883). Data persistence and analytics are carried out with TimescaleDB, accessed over the standard PostgreSQL wire protocol. The system therefore relies on standard TCP/IP networking for both MQTT and database traffic; no specific network topology, bandwidth, latency, reliability, redundancy or security protocols beyond the MQTT and PostgreSQL defaults are mentioned."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "Both the physical and digital twin stacks are deployed on a single personal computer (edge device). The Python applications (crane interface, control, logging, trajectory generation, simulation, validation, dashboard) and supporting services (TimescaleDB, Eclipse Mosquitto MQTT broker) run in Docker containers orchestrated by a docker‑compose file. The deployment is a single‑node edge configuration; no horizontal scaling or high‑availability features are described."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The system adheres to a set of open standards: sensor data are transmitted using MQTT over an ActiveMQ broker, time‑series data are stored in InfluxDB (built on PostgreSQL), the Air‑Quality twin is described using AutomationML, and architecture diagrams are created with the C4 model notation. Deployment is platform‑agnostic through Docker containers. All source code is distributed under the MIT license as indicated by the LICENSE file in the GitHub repository."
]
